  "text": "In practice, each densely connected layer has L sub-layers. The dimensions of these sub-layers d hidden are decided by L and the input feature dimension d. In AGGCNs, we use d hidden = d/L. For example, if the densely connected layer has 3 sub-layers and the input dimension is 300, the hidden dimension of each sub-layer will be d hidden = d/L = 300/3 = 100. Then we concatenate the output of each sub-layer to form the new representation. Therefore, the output dimension is 300 (3 × 100). Different from the GCN model whose hidden dimension is larger than or equal to the input dimension, the AGGCN model shrinks the hidden dimension as the number of layers increases in order to improves the parameter efficiency similar to DenseNets [CITATION_1] ).",
